Introduction ¶

Does how much a student studies affect their final grade? What about participating in extra curricular activities or going out
with friends? There are many attributes of a student's life that may or may not affect their performance in school. Wouldn't
you love to finally prove to your parents once and for all that your lack of studying isn't affecting your grades? Or maybe
it does and your parents were right all along...

In this tutorial we will investigate how some of these attributes affect the final grade of a student. We use a dataset
found in the UCL Machine Learning Repository curated by Paulo Cortez (see sources) which includes data from two Portugese
secondary schools. The dataset features grades in two courses: Math and Portugese language. We will go into more depth about
the various other attributes highlighted by this dataset including specific column names. Then, we will investigate which
attributes might affect a student's grade and do some hypothesis testing and modelling to gain some insight about how
a student can get that A!

From Kaggle.com, where I initially found this dataset, we have the following descriptions for each column:

Attribute Information:

  • school - student's school (binary: 'GP' - Gabriel Pereira or 'MS' - Mousinho da Silveira)
  • sex - student's sex (binary: 'F' - female or 'M' - male)
  • age - student's age (numeric: from 15 to 22)
  • address - student's home address type (binary: 'U' - urban or 'R' - rural)
  • famsize - family size (binary: 'LE3' - less or equal to 3 or 'GT3' - greater than 3)
  • Pstatus - parent's cohabitation status (binary: 'T' - living together or 'A' - apart)
  • Medu - mother's education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 - 5th to 9th grade, 3 - secondary education or 4 - higher education)
  • Fedu - father's education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 - 5th to 9th grade, 3 - secondary education or 4 - higher education)
  • Mjob - mother's job (nominal: 'teacher', 'health' care related, civil 'services' (e.g. administrative or police), 'at_home' or 'other')
  • Fjob - father's job (nominal: 'teacher', 'health' care related, civil 'services' (e.g. administrative or police), 'at_home' or 'other')
  • reason - reason to choose this school (nominal: close to 'home', school 'reputation', 'course' preference or 'other')
  • guardian - student's guardian (nominal: 'mother', 'father' or 'other')
  • traveltime - home to school travel time (numeric: 1 - <15 min., 2 - 15 to 30 min., 3 - 30 min. to 1 hour, or 4 - >1 hour)
  • studytime - weekly study time (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours)
  • failures - number of past class failures (numeric: n if 1<=n<3, else 4)
  • schoolsup - extra educational support (binary: yes or no)
  • famsup - family educational support (binary: yes or no)
  • paid - extra paid classes within the course subject (Math or Portuguese) (binary: yes or no)
  • activities - extra-curricular activities (binary: yes or no)
  • nursery - attended nursery school (binary: yes or no)
  • higher - wants to take higher education (binary: yes or no)
  • internet - Internet access at home (binary: yes or no)
  • romantic - with a romantic relationship (binary: yes or no)
  • famrel - quality of family relationships (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent)
  • freetime - free time after school (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • goout - going out with friends (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • Dalc - workday alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • Walc - weekend alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  • health - current health status (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - very good)
  • absences - number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93)

Grades are related with the course subject, Math or Portuguese:

G1 - first period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)\ G2 - second period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)\ G3 - final grade (numeric: from 0 to 20, output target)

too much time analyzing features that obviously won't give us very useful resorts. Plus, we get to learn more about our data
and see pretty graphs too! :)

In [26]:

From the above plot, it appears that paid extra classes do actually improve student performance. The blue curve
represents the grade distribution of students that paid for extra classes, and as we can see it has a higher density
of grades at the average grade of around 10. And we can see by the small peak on the left side of the graph
that these students received a grade of 0 less often as well.

Linear Regression ¶

We'll start out by doing some linear regression, which is one of the most commonly used types of modeling!

First, we need to split our data up into a training set and a testing set to evaluate our model!

In [43]:
# splitting the data
X = data[['studytime', 'failures', 'higher', 'paid']]   # only using the features we explored earlier
y = data['G3']   # only looking at predicting the final grade
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.25, random_state=42)

Now we can train the data using the linear regression model!

In [44]:
model = LinearRegression()
# model.fit(X_train, y_train)

When I tried to fit the model, I got an error saying that there was a failure to convert to float from string "yes".
This issue comes from the fact that we still have categorical values in our data, so we will need to address it first!
Since we only have two variables here that are causing the issue ("higher" and "paid"), I will just manually
encode these columns using a 0 to represent a "no" and a 1 to represent a "yes". This is a simple version of one
hot encoding in which we use binary values to represent the categories of a categorical variable. Note: this works when
the variable has few categories like in our case, but if there are too many this becomes a very inefficient
approach.

One Hot Encoding

In [109]:
# using python map function to convert yes/no to 1/0
data['paid'] = data['paid'].map(dict(yes=1.0, no=0.0))
data['higher'] = data['higher'].map(dict(yes=1.0, no=0.0))

In [113]:
predictions = model.predict(X_test)

slope = model.coef_
intercept = model.intercept_

def myfunc(y_test):
    return slope*y_test+intercept
mymodel = list(map(myfunc,y_test))

Just at a glance, it doesn't seem like our linear regression results were all that great, since we can't see
much of a trend in the resulting graph. However, let's take a look at some actual metrics to see how our model did.

In [116]:
from sklearn import metrics
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score

print('MAE:', metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions))
print('MSE:', metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions))
print('RMSE:', np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions)))
print("Explain variance score =", round(metrics.explained_variance_score(y_test, predictions), 2)) 
print('r2 Score:', r2_score(y_test, predictions))

MAE: 3.5560358128799874
MSE: 20.425151744322537
RMSE: 4.519419403454667
Explain variance score = 0.07
r2 Score: 0.07082645700652956

We can see that we have a very large mean squared error. This is because this metric is extra vulnerable to outliers,
and in this case we have a large amount of them since we have a significant number of 0 grades. Also, our
rsquared score was also quite low with an ideal being 1.0. Let's try a different model! Or perhaps we might need
to use some different variables with higher correlations.

To do the latter, just be looking at the correlation heatmap from earlier, we can see that G1 and G2 are highly
correlated with the final grade. So, to show how linear regression can work, we can easily make it perform better
by including these columns in our test data. However, since we already know the grades to be highly correlated, it will
not provide much useful insight.

Given that the outliers of the 0 grades seem to be hurting our models, let's try excluding them.

What if we include all of the features? (Excluding G1, G2)

To do this we must address all of the categorical variables using one hot encoding. So I will use the pandas function
get_dummies to do this on all of these attributes.
